{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #1074: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. Let $S$ be the set of all $m\\geq 1$ such that there exists a prime $p\\not\\equiv 1\\pmod{m}$ such that $m!+1\\equiv 0\\pmod{p}$. Does\\[\\lim \\frac{\\lvert S\\cap [1,x]\\rvert}{x}\\]exist? What is it?\n\nSimilarly, if $P$ is the set of all primes $p$ such that there exists an $m$ with $p\\not\\equiv 1\\pmod{m}$ such that $m!+1\\equiv 0\\pmod{p}$, then does\\[\\lim \\frac{\\lvert P\\cap [1,x]\\rvert}{\\pi(x)}\\]exist? What is it? Current best: The frequency with which the EHS numbers occur - most often in long sequences of consecutive integers - makes us believe that their asymptotic density exists and is unity. Prize: no. OEIS: A063980, A064164. Tags: number theory.","id":"vf_b5c114f9cc0d8c77","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos1074.erdos_1074.variants.EHSNumbers_infinite https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos1074.erdos_1074.variants.EHSNumbers_infinite.","id":"vf_c8623166a76a535c","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/1074.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_b5c114f9cc0d8c77","source_root":"sha256:d3db36661e28b7570fc8704bf8455b80d8382beded47d069f2c386144d90a238","target":"erdos:1074","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_c8623166a76a535c","source_root":"sha256:d3db36661e28b7570fc8704bf8455b80d8382beded47d069f2c386144d90a238","target":"erdos:1074","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepted findings.","inferred":true,"relation":"synthesized_